---
import BaseLayout from '@layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
---
<BaseLayout title="Ann Fritz — Ann Fritz Designs | Heat & Glo Architects" description="Ann Fritz of Ann Fritz Designs specifies Heat & Glo for custom residential projects in the Pacific Northwest, where the fireplace bridges interior architecture and the surrounding landscape." noIndex={true}>

  <!-- HERO -->
  <section style="position:relative; min-height:520px; display:flex; align-items:flex-end; overflow:hidden;">
    <img
      src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/96f4f3b6-bb4e-4004-a797-85aa7179b3bb/HNG-True_ForgedArch"
      alt="Traditional fireplace in a stone hearth with Coastal Chic furnishings and decorated shelves on each side"
      style="position:absolute; inset:0; width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover; object-position:center;"
      loading="eager"
    />
    <div style="position:absolute; inset:0; background:linear-gradient(to top, rgba(12,18,14,0.84) 0%, rgba(12,18,14,0.42) 55%, rgba(12,18,14,0.12) 100%);"></div>
    <div style="position:relative; max-width:820px; padding:3rem 2rem; color:#fff;">
      <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.14em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#a8d5b0; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">Designer Feature</p>
      <h1 style="font-size:clamp(2rem,5vw,3.25rem); font-weight:800; line-height:1.1; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Ann Fritz</h1>
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:400; opacity:0.9; margin:0;">Ann Fritz Designs &nbsp;&middot;&nbsp; Custom Residential, Pacific Northwest</p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <main style="max-width:860px; margin:0 auto; padding:3rem 1.5rem;">

    <!-- INTRO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Grounded in Region, Built for How People Actually Live</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Pacific Northwest residential design operates under a specific set of pressures that designers from other regions don't often have to reconcile. The natural landscape is extraordinary and immediately present: mountains, water, old-growth timber, and a grey-green light that doesn't behave the way light behaves elsewhere. The client base is sophisticated and frequently comes with strong opinions about material provenance, environmental stewardship, and the relationship between inside and outside. And the weather, for a significant portion of the year, wants a fire.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        Ann Fritz built Ann Fritz Designs on a clear premise: the interior of a Pacific Northwest home should be a conversation with its site, not a retreat from it. That means material palettes drawn from regional quarries, reclaimed sources, and living-edge wood. It means views treated as framed compositions. And it means the fireplace understood as the thermal and visual center of the room, a thing that earns its mass by what it gives back to the people sitting in front of it.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        Ann's work tends toward warm natural finishes: stone with visible grain, plaster with texture, wood that carries its history. The fireplace surround is typically the room's primary material statement. The unit behind it has to support that aesthetic without fighting it. Clean lines, a dependable flame profile, and the ability to coexist with heavy non-combustible surrounds without requiring compromises in clearance or finish alignment.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- PULL QUOTE -->
    <section style="border-left:4px solid #3d7a4a; padding:1.25rem 1.75rem; background:#f3f8f4; margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <p style="font-size:1.125rem; line-height:1.7; color:#2a2a2a; font-style:italic; margin:0 0 0.75rem;">
        "In the Pacific Northwest, a fireplace is not optional. It's part of how a room earns its right to exist through November. The question is whether the unit behind the surround supports the material story or undercuts it. The True Series gives me room to tell the story the way I want to tell it."
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:0.8125rem; color:#6b6b6b; margin:0; font-style:normal; letter-spacing:0.04em; text-transform:uppercase;">Paraphrased from Ann Fritz's ProAdvantage program onboarding &mdash; illustrative, not a verified direct quotation</p>
    </section>

    <!-- WHY HEAT & GLO -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Why Ann Fritz Designs Specifies Heat &amp; Glo</h2>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The True Series is Ann's primary specification in traditional and transitional residential contexts because it accepts the kind of surround her material palette requires. Full-height stone, a robust timber mantel, or a plaster chase that wraps the fireplace from floor to ceiling, these are not unusual in a Pacific Northwest custom home, and they come with clearance requirements that need to be resolved in design development, not in the field. The True Series accommodates those conditions without demanding geometry compromises that show in the finished install.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The flame character in the True is also the right register for Ann's work. Her clients are not looking for a technological statement. They want fire that looks like fire. The natural log media options in the True line support that expectation without requiring Ann to convince anyone of anything. The decision reads as obvious in the finished room.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        For projects with a more contemporary interior language, the Mezzo becomes the conversation. Open-plan homes that blur the kitchen-dining-living threshold, or a study with a clean plaster wall, respond to the Mezzo's linear format in a way a traditional firebox doesn't satisfy. Ann carries both specifications into her typical project portfolio, and the ability to source both through the same ProAdvantage relationship simplifies the dealer coordination leg of the design process.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- TYPICAL PROJECT SHAPE -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">The Shape of an Ann Fritz Designs Project</h2>
      <h3 style="font-size:1.125rem; font-weight:600; color:#3d7a4a; margin:0 0 1rem;">Site, Material, and the Hearth Decision</h3>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        A typical Ann Fritz Designs engagement is a custom residential build or substantial whole-home renovation on a site where the landscape is doing most of the visual work. The client has usually already made large decisions about building form and exterior material, often stone, board-and-batten, or a combination of mass and glass. Ann's role is to bring interior coherence to those exterior commitments, and the fireplace is the first interior element that conversation touches.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0 0 1.25rem;">
        The hearth decision shapes the room's thermal zone, which shapes furniture placement, which shapes traffic patterns through the living area. Ann resolves the fireplace specification early, during schematic design, and treats the Heat and Glo unit selection as a structural decision rather than a finish-level choice. The surround material, the mantel profile, and the flue chase treatment all follow from that first decision.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size:1.0625rem; line-height:1.8; color:#3a3a3a; margin:0;">
        Her clients tend to be families who use their homes through all four seasons. The fireplace is expected to carry its weight on a grey October Tuesday as naturally as it does at a holiday gathering. IntelliFire's scheduling and remote operation capabilities support that kind of habitual, low-friction use, which matters more than dramatic performance in a home that people actually live in every day.
      </p>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 1 -->
    <section style="background:#1a1a1a; color:#fff; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#a8d5b0; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Trade Program</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Join ProAdvantage</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; opacity:0.8; margin:0;">Dedicated trade support, priority access, and project resources for design professionals.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/pro/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Explore ProAdvantage</a>
    </section>

    <!-- INSTALLATION CARDS -->
    <section style="margin-bottom:3.5rem;">
      <h2 style="font-size:1.5rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 1.5rem;">Sample Installations in the Ann Fritz Register</h2>
      <div style="display:grid; grid-template-columns:repeat(auto-fill,minmax(240px,1fr)); gap:1.5rem;">

        <!-- Card 1 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/96f4f3b6-bb4e-4004-a797-85aa7179b3bb/HNG-True_ForgedArch"
              alt="Traditional fireplace in a stone hearth with warm furnishings and flanking shelves"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">True Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Stone-Surround Great Room</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Full-height stone, flanking built-in shelving, natural log media. The PNW hearth that does not have to announce itself.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 2 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/c220ce20-e963-4c07-85ca-83fa16359ef4/Nest-Out-West-Basem"
              alt="Warm residential basement remodel with fireplace as the living room anchor"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">True Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Finished Lower Level</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">A secondary living level where the fireplace anchors a cozy, family-use space. Material continuity with the floors above.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

        <!-- Card 3 -->
        <article style="border:1px solid #e5e0db; border-radius:4px; overflow:hidden;">
          <div style="position:relative; aspect-ratio:4/3; overflow:hidden;">
            <img
              src="https://hearthnhome.getbynder.com/transform/d46ab388-275f-4983-b659-7c4cd454dcf5/img-pdp-mezzo-room-"
              alt="Heat and Glo Mezzo linear gas fireplace with ribbon flame in a contemporary living room"
              style="width:100%; height:100%; object-fit:cover;"
              loading="lazy"
            />
          </div>
          <div style="padding:1rem 1.125rem;">
            <p style="font-size:0.6875rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.1em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#c44a08; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Mezzo Series</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; font-weight:600; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.5rem;">Contemporary Interior Feature Wall</p>
            <p style="font-size:0.875rem; line-height:1.6; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Linear format, ribbon flame, plaster surround. The contemporary counterpart in Ann's portfolio when plan geometry calls for it.</p>
          </div>
        </article>

      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- CTA BAND 2 -->
    <section style="background:#f3f8f4; border:1px solid #c2ddc8; padding:2.5rem 2rem; border-radius:4px; margin-bottom:3.5rem; display:flex; flex-wrap:wrap; align-items:center; gap:1.5rem; justify-content:space-between;">
      <div>
        <p style="font-size:0.75rem; font-weight:700; letter-spacing:0.12em; text-transform:uppercase; color:#3d7a4a; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Dealer Network</p>
        <p style="font-size:1.25rem; font-weight:700; color:#1a1a1a; margin:0 0 0.375rem;">Find a Local Dealer</p>
        <p style="font-size:0.9375rem; color:#5a5a5a; margin:0;">Connect with a Heat and Glo dealer for spec sheets, clearance documentation, and display showroom access near your project.</p>
      </div>
      <a href="/where-to-buy/" style="background:#c44a08; color:#fff; font-weight:700; font-size:0.9375rem; text-decoration:none; padding:0.875rem 1.75rem; border-radius:3px; white-space:nowrap; display:inline-block;">Dealer Locator</a>
    </section>

    <p style="color:#888; font-size:0.875rem; border-top:1px solid #e5e0db; padding-top:1.5rem;"><a href="/architect/" style="color:#c44a08; text-decoration:none;">Back to all architects</a></p>
  </main>

</BaseLayout>
